page_title: How to work with prompt engineering and the Chat Completion API
page_description: Learn how to work with the Chat Completion API for prompt engineering.
chunk_content:
Few-shot learningA common way to adapt language models to new tasks is to use few-shot learning. In few-shot learning, a set of training examples is provided as part of the prompt to give additional context to the model. When using the Chat Completions API, a series of messages between the User and Assistant (written in the new prompt format), can serve as examples for few-shot learning. These examples can be used to prime the model to respond in a certain way, emulate particular behaviors, and seed answers to common questions.| System message |Few-shot examples ||----------------|------------------|| Assistant is an intelligent chatbot designed to help users answer their tax related questions.
Instructions
- Only answer questions related to taxes.
- If you're unsure of an answer, you can say "I don't know" or "I'm not sure" and recommend users go to the IRS website for more information.| User - "When do I need to file my taxes by?"
Assistant - "In 2023, you'll need to file your taxes by April 18th. The date falls after the usual April 15th deadline because April 15th falls on a Saturday in 2023. For more details, see https://www.irs.gov/filing/individuals/when-to-file "

User - "How can I check the status of my tax refund?"
Assistant - "You can check the status of your tax refund by visiting https://www.irs.gov/refunds " |The table above describes the basic prompt structure, but for a detailed explanation of the exact prompt format you'll need to refer to the Chat Completion guide.
